            "answer_text": "Let Z= x+3y and W=x-3y then solving for x and y we have that x= (Z+W)/2 and y= (Z-W)/6 hence f(Z,W)= 12*(Z+W)(Z-W)/12 = Z^2 - W^2 . Therefore f(x,y)= x^2 - y^2. We have got the answer. But the beautiful thing to notice here is that Z^2 - W^2=1 is a rectangular hyperbola whose eccentricity is \u221a2 Which under the affine transformations x= (Z+W)/2 and y= (Z-W)/6 give the familiar hyperbola y= 1/12x. This is the motivation behind the problem posed. ",
